# CSS Text Properties

CSS text properties are used to control the appearance and formatting of text on a webpage.

---

## 1. `font-size`

Sets the size of the text.

**Example:**

```css
p {
  font-size: 18px;
}
```

---

## 2. `font-family`

Specifies the font (typeface) of the text.

**Example:**

```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
```

---

## 3. `font-style`

Changes the style of the text.

**Common Values:**

- `normal`
- `italic`
- `oblique`

**Example:**

```css
p {
  font-style: italic;
}
```

---

## 4. `text-transform`

Changes the capitalization of text.

**Common Values:**

- `uppercase` → ALL CAPITAL LETTERS
- `lowercase` → all small letters
- `capitalize` → First Letter Of Each Word
- `none` → Default text

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  text-transform: uppercase;
}
```

---

## 5. `text-align`

Aligns text horizontally.

**Common Values:**

- `left`
- `center`
- `right`
- `justify`

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  text-align: center;
}
```

---

## 6. `line-height`

Controls the vertical space between lines of text.

**Example:**

```css
p {
  line-height: 1.6;
}
```

---

## 7. `font-weight`

Controls the thickness (boldness) of the text.

**Common Values:**

- `normal`
- `bold`
- `100` to `900`

**Example:**

```css
h1 {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

---

## 8. `list-style`

Changes the appearance of list markers.

**Common Values:**

- `disc`
- `circle`
- `square`
- `none`

**Example:**

```css
ul {
  list-style: square;
}
```

To remove bullets:

```css
ul {
  list-style: none;
}
```

---

# Summary Table

| Property         | Purpose                                            |
| ---------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| `font-size`      | Sets the text size.                                |
| `font-family`    | Specifies the font.                                |
| `font-style`     | Changes the text style (normal, italic).           |
| `text-transform` | Changes letter capitalization.                     |
| `text-align`     | Aligns the text.                                   |
| `line-height`    | Sets the space between lines.                      |
| `font-weight`    | Controls the boldness of the text.                 |
| `list-style`     | Changes or removes list markers (bullets/numbers). |

---

# Key Points

- Use **`font-size`** to control text size.
- Use **`font-family`** to choose a font.
- Use **`font-style`** for italic or oblique text.
- Use **`text-transform`** to change letter casing.
- Use **`text-align`** to align text.
- Use **`line-height`** to improve readability.
- Use **`font-weight`** to make text lighter or bolder.
- Use **`list-style`** to customize or remove list bullets and numbering.

# Combining Selectors

**Combining selectors** allows you to apply the same style to multiple elements or to select elements based on their relationship.

---

## 1. List Selector (Grouping Selector)

A **list selector** is used to apply the **same CSS styles to multiple elements**.

Instead of writing separate CSS rules, you can group selectors using a **comma (`,`)**.

### Syntax

```css id="7a2u7l"
selector1,
selector2,
selector3 {
  property: value;
}
```

### Example

```css id="5ik1rd"
h1,
h2,
p {
  color: blue;
}
```

This applies the same text color (**blue**) to all `<h1>`, `<h2>`, and `<p>` elements.

### Why Use It?

- Reduces duplicate code.
- Makes CSS cleaner and easier to maintain.

---

## 2. Descendant Selector

A **descendant selector** selects an element that is **inside another element**, regardless of how deeply it is nested.

It uses a **space** between the selectors.

### Syntax

```css id="opzm50"
parent child {
  property: value;
}
```

### Example

#### HTML

```html id="xrlm5e"
<article>
  <p>This paragraph is inside an article.</p>
</article>

<p>This paragraph is outside the article.</p>
```

#### CSS

```css id="jlwm4m"
article p {
  color: red;
}
```

### Result

- ✅ The paragraph **inside** `<article>` becomes **red**.
- ❌ The paragraph **outside** `<article>` is **not affected**.

### Why Use It?

Use a descendant selector when you want to style elements **only within a specific parent element**.

---

# Quick Reference

| Selector                | Syntax          | Purpose                                         |
| ----------------------- | --------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| **List Selector**       | `h1, h2, p { }` | Applies the same styles to multiple elements.   |
| **Descendant Selector** | `article p { }` | Selects child elements inside a parent element. |

---

# Key Points

- **List Selector (`,`)** → Styles multiple elements using one CSS rule.
- **Descendant Selector (space)** → Styles elements that are inside another element.
- Group selectors with a **comma**.
- Select descendants using a **space** between selectors.

Class & ID Selector

# CSS Selectors

A **CSS Selector** is used to select HTML elements so that you can apply styles to them.

---

## 1. Class Selector (`.`)

A **class selector** is used to style **one or more HTML elements** that share the same class name.

### HTML

```html id="kzvk80"
<h1 class="heading">Welcome</h1>

<p class="heading">Hello World!</p>
```

### CSS

```css id="1g9jti"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}
```

**Output:**

- Both the `<h1>` and `<p>` elements become **blue** because they have the same class.

---

# 2. ID Selector (`#`)

An **ID selector** is used to style **one unique HTML element**.

### HTML

```html id="ewcqz5"
<h1 id="title">Welcome</h1>
```

### CSS

```css id="ylv0jh"
#title {
  color: red;
}
```

Only the element with `id="title"` will be styled.

---

# Difference Between `class` and `id`

| Class (`class`)                  | ID (`id`)                                                       |
| -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Starts with `.` in CSS           | Starts with `#` in CSS                                          |
| Can be used on multiple elements | Should be used only once per page                               |
| Reusable                         | Unique                                                          |
| Best for styling                 | Mainly used for unique elements, JavaScript, or page navigation |

---

# Why Use `class` Instead of `id` for CSS?

In modern web development, **classes are preferred for styling**.

### Reasons

### 1. Reusable

One class can be applied to many elements.

```html id="e57bgx"
<h2 class="heading">HTML</h2>

<h2 class="heading">CSS</h2>

<h2 class="heading">JavaScript</h2>
```

```css id="6z5gfe"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}
```

All three headings use the same CSS.

---

### 2. Easier to Maintain

If you want to change the style later, update **one class** instead of multiple IDs.

---

### 3. Better for Large Projects

Large websites often have hundreds of elements with the same design. Classes allow you to reuse styles instead of writing duplicate CSS.

---

### 4. IDs Have Higher Specificity

An ID selector (`#`) has a higher priority than a class selector (`.`).

This can make your CSS harder to override and maintain.

Example:

```css id="i2t02j"
.heading {
  color: blue;
}

#title {
  color: red;
}
```

If an element has both:

```html id="m5k8y8"
<h1 id="title" class="heading">Hello</h1>
```

The text will be **red** because the ID selector has higher specificity.

---

# When to Use `id`

Use an `id` when the element is **unique** on the page.

Examples:

- Main navigation
- Hero section
- Login form
- Unique banner

It is also commonly used for:

- JavaScript (`document.getElementById()`)
- Linking to a section of a page

Example:

```html id="g4q0ps"
<section id="about">...</section>

<a href="#about">Go to About Section</a>
```

---

# When to Use `class`

Use a `class` whenever you want to:

- Style multiple elements.
- Reuse the same styles.
- Build scalable and maintainable CSS.

---

# Key Points

- `.` → Class Selector
- `#` → ID Selector
- A **class** can be reused on multiple elements.
- An **ID** should be unique on a webpage.
- **Use classes for CSS styling.**
- **Use IDs for unique elements, JavaScript, or anchor links.**

# Working with Colors in CSS

CSS provides different ways to define colors for text, backgrounds, borders, and other elements.

---

# RGB Color Model

**RGB** stands for:

- **R** → Red
- **G** → Green
- **B** → Blue

Each color has a value between **0 and 255**.

Example:

```css id="3cpj3g"
h1 {
  color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
}
```

This displays **red** because:

- Red = 255
- Green = 0
- Blue = 0

---

# Ways to Define Colors in CSS

## 1. RGB / RGBA Notation

### RGB

Uses Red, Green, and Blue values.

```css id="6jlwm7"
color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
```

Example:

```css id="j6jj6n"
p {
  color: rgb(0, 128, 255);
}
```

---

### RGBA

RGBA is the same as RGB but adds an **Alpha (A)** value for transparency.

Alpha values range from:

- `0` → Fully transparent
- `1` → Fully visible

Example:

```css id="n0l8u4"
background-color: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5);
```

This creates a **semi-transparent red** background.

---

## 2. Hexadecimal Notation

Hexadecimal (Hex) colors begin with `#` followed by **six hexadecimal digits**.

```css id="0ezmmy"
color: #1098ad;
```

Structure:

```text id="taw0vf"
#RRGGBB
```

Examples:

| Color | Hex Code  |
| ----- | --------- |
| Red   | `#ff0000` |
| Green | `#00ff00` |
| Blue  | `#0000ff` |
| Black | `#000000` |
| White | `#ffffff` |

---

# Shades of Grey

Grey colors are created by using **equal values** for Red, Green, and Blue.

Examples:

| Color      | Hex Code  |
| ---------- | --------- |
| Black      | `#000000` |
| Dark Grey  | `#333333` |
| Grey       | `#666666` |
| Light Grey | `#cccccc` |
| White      | `#ffffff` |

---

# Border Property

The `border` property adds a border around an HTML element.

### Syntax

```css id="j5ztmh"
border: width style color;
```

### Example

```css id="fck2mj"
border: 5px solid #1098ad;
```

### Breakdown

| Value     | Meaning      |
| --------- | ------------ |
| `5px`     | Border width |
| `solid`   | Border style |
| `#1098ad` | Border color |

Example:

```css id="gzux1w"
h1 {
  border: 5px solid #1098ad;
}
```

---

# Summary Table

| Property  | Purpose                                           |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| `rgb()`   | Defines colors using Red, Green, and Blue values. |
| `rgba()`  | Defines colors with transparency.                 |
| `#RRGGBB` | Defines colors using hexadecimal values.          |
| `border`  | Adds a border around an element.                  |

---

# Key Points

- RGB uses **Red, Green, and Blue** values (0–255).
- RGBA adds **transparency** using the Alpha value.
- Hexadecimal colors start with `#` and contain six characters.
- Grey shades are created by using equal RGB values.
- The `border` property requires **width, style, and color**.

# CSS Pseudo-Classes

## What are Pseudo-Classes?

A **pseudo-class** is a keyword added to a CSS selector to style an element based on its **state** or **position** in the HTML document.

Pseudo-classes begin with a **colon (`:`)**.

### Syntax

```css id="5m9tnb"
selector:pseudo-class {
  property: value;
}
```

---

# `:first-child`

The `:first-child` pseudo-class selects the **first child element** inside its parent.

### HTML

```html id="rppxq8"
<ul>
  <li>HTML</li>
  <li>CSS</li>
  <li>JavaScript</li>
</ul>
```

### CSS

```css id="n0m5tb"
li:first-child {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

### Output

- **HTML** ← Bold
- CSS
- JavaScript

---

# `:last-child`

The `:last-child` pseudo-class selects the **last child element** inside its parent.

### CSS

```css id="fdt3gt"
li:last-child {
  font-style: italic;
}
```

### Output

- HTML
- CSS
- _JavaScript_ ← Italic

---

# Using Both Together

### CSS

```css id="p1np6g"
li:first-child {
  font-weight: bold;
}

li:last-child {
  font-style: italic;
}
```

### Result

- **HTML** ← Bold
- CSS
- _JavaScript_ ← Italic

---

# Common Pseudo-Classes

| Pseudo-Class   | Purpose                                               |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| `:first-child` | Selects the first child element.                      |
| `:last-child`  | Selects the last child element.                       |
| `:hover`       | Applies styles when the mouse hovers over an element. |
| `:active`      | Applies styles while an element is being clicked.     |
| `:visited`     | Styles links that have already been visited.          |
| `:link`        | Styles unvisited links.                               |

---

# Key Points

- A pseudo-class starts with a **colon (`:`)**.
- It styles an element based on its **state** or **position**.
- `:first-child` selects the **first child**.
- `:last-child` selects the **last child**.

---

# Easy Way to Remember

```text id="gt7vyl"
:first-child  → First child element

:last-child   → Last child element

:hover        → Mouse is over the element

:active       → Element is being clicked
```
